At .eco, we try to help people make more **eco-friendly technology choices**. One of the most impactful decisions that you make when setting up a new website is [choosing where to host it](/news/where-you-host-your-website-really-matters/). That’s why whenever someone [searches for a .eco domain](/search/) on this site, we highlight domain retailers and web hosts that are [operating more sustainably](/news/eco-friendly-web-host/), such as by being powered by renewable energy, operating a highly energy-efficient data center or having clear environmental policies and commitments.

To understand how many people are heeding this advice, we annually review all active .eco domains to see how many are using sustainable web hosting. We do this by checking every .eco domain against [Green Web Check](https://www.thegreenwebfoundation.org/green-web-check/) from the Green Web Foundation.

This is our fourth year doing this analysis. Every year, we've gained new insights reviewing this data. We're excited to share what we've learned.

### Methodology

First, we should have a quick word about our approach. It's a bit technical, so feel free to skip over this if you want to jump to the results.

For this analysis we are only considering .eco domains that have an "active website". This means that:
- the domain name should resolve to a valid website that returns a successful HTTP status code (200)
- we exclude domains that redirect to a websites that isn't using a .eco domain
- we exclude domains associated with a registrar parking or construction page or that are otherwise devoid of content

There are a few reasons why we focus only on active websites:
1. People care more about and have more control over their actual website than a parking page
2. Our baseline contains only valid websites, so it provides a better basis of comparison (more on this later)

### 2025 Results

As of September 29, 2025, **45% of active .eco websites** use an eco-friendly web hosting provider. This is a slight increase from last year.

.eco domains use 95 different green web hosting providers. This is down quite significantly (38%) from last year. Over the past few years, we have seen the number of different green web hosts grow each year as more providers register with the Green Web Foundation. This is the first time we've seen the number of providers drop. It is likely due to [clean up of the hosting directory done by the Green Web Foundation](https://www.thegreenwebfoundation.org/news/an-update-on-finding-representatives-for-large-hosting-providers/), but it does have some fairly significant implications which we'll dig into later.

